<paper id="1658032593"><title>On the Decidability of Model Checking for Several µ-calculi and Petri Nets</title><year>1994</year><authors><author org="University of Edinburgh," id="2123449190">Javier Esparza</author></authors><n_citation>64</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1514194201</reference><reference>1598641851</reference><reference>1964087553</reference><reference>1989788631</reference><reference>1999917306</reference><reference>2033071128</reference><reference>2044858512</reference><reference>2053421425</reference><reference>2106001218</reference><reference>2164003033</reference><reference>2295768847</reference></references><venue id="2756386172" type="C">Colloquium on trees in Algebra and Programming</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0017477</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.43219">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.54882">Model checking</keyword><keyword weight="0.63026">Petri net</keyword><keyword weight="0.4012">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.48335">Finite-state machine</keyword><keyword weight="0.57874">Decidability</keyword><keyword weight="0.66072">Stochastic Petri net</keyword><keyword weight="0.50742">Temporal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.4593">Time complexity</keyword><keyword weight="0.5154">Undecidable problem</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>The decidability of the model checking problem for several μ-calculi and Petri nets is analysed. The linear time μ-calculus without atomic sentences is decidable; if simple atomic sentences are added, it becomes undecidable. A very simple subset of the modal μ-calculus is undecidable.</abstract></paper>